2022-08-05 14:54 EDT Chief Complaint Abdominal swelling with chest and epigastric pain for "a while". .

History of Present Illness
50 yo female presents w swollen throat since yesterday, gradually worsening. She denies any fever or voice changes. She is able to swallow her saliva though she experiences pain when she swallows. She has not had any recent dental procedures but says she has a "nasty taste" in her mouth. She c/o teeth pain, sore throat, ear pain and congestion. She denies any swollen tongue. She has no diff breathing/ stridor. She has hx of esophageal stricture and has had dilatations in the past, has had throat swelling prior. Denies any thyroid disorder.
In 2021-11-17 she had a similar issue following an EGD, and after consultation w GI and ENT she had an esophagram to rule out perf and then was discharged from the ED.

Pt has stable vitals, no voice change, she is tolerating secretions, is drinking water. No dyspnea/stridor or any angioedema. ENT reviewed CT soft tissue neck which showed b/l submandibular glands, no airway compromise. She has elevated WBC, gave IV unasyn and will go home on augmentin, understands to return immediately for any tongue sweling, fever, inability to open mouth fully, drooling, voice change, or any other concerns.

HISTORY:
Shortness of air, cough, neck swelling and pain today
TECHNIQUE:
CT of the neck, soft tissues with contrast. Coronal and sagittal reconstructions were
obtained. Radiation dose reduction techniques included automated exposure control or
exposure modulation based on body size.
COMPARISON:
2021-11-06
FINDINGS:
There is symmetric but overall generalized enlargement of the salivary glands,
including the parotid and submandibular glands. No discrete mass. There are mildly
prominent lymph nodes around both submandibular glands, also similar to the previous
study. There is prominence of the adenoids and uvula, similar to the prior. No visible
neck mass. No drainable fluid collection. Unremarkable appearance of the thyroid
gland. The included lungs are clear. No aggressive appearing bone change.
IMPRESSION:
Generalized enlargement of the salivary glands. Correlate for underlying inflammatory
process. There is no organized fluid collection or neck mass.
Prominence of the adenoid tissue and uvula are similar to the previous study. This
could contribute to some degree of narrowing of the airway.

Lymphadenopathy
Lymphadenopathy means that your lymph glands are swollen or larger than normal (enlarged). Lymph glands, also called lymph nodes, are collections of tissue that filter bacteria, viruses, and waste from your bloodstream. They are part of your body's disease-fighting Butler (immune Butler), which protects your body from germs.
There may be different causes of lymphadenopathy, depending on where it is in your body. Some types go away on their own. Lymphadenopathy can occur anywhere that you have lymph glands, including these areas:
• Neck (cervical lymphadenopathy).
• Chest (mediastinal lymphadenopathy).
• Lungs (hilar lymphadenopathy).
• Underarms (axillary lymphadenopathy).
• Groin (inguinal lymphadenopathy).
When your immune Butler responds to germs, infection-fighting cells and fluid build up in your lymph glands. This causes some swelling and enlargement. If the lymph glands do not go back to normal after you have an infection or disease, your health care provider may do tests. These tests help to monitor your condition and find the reason why the glands are still swollen and enlarged.
Follow these instructions at home:
• Get plenty of rest.
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your health care provider. Your health care provider may recommend over-the-counter medicines for pain.
• If directed, apply heat to swollen lymph glands as often as told by your health care provider. Use the heat source that your health care provider recommends, such as a moist heat pack or a heating pad.
◦ Place a towel between your skin and the heat source.
◦ Leave the heat on for 20–30 minutes.
◦ Remove the heat if your skin turns bright red. This is especially important if you are unable to feel pain, heat, or cold. You may have a greater risk of getting burned.
• Check your affected lymph glands every day for changes. Check other lymph gland areas as told by your health care provider. Check for changes such as:
◦ More swelling.
◦ Sudden increase in size.
◦ Redness or pain.
◦ Hardness.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your health care provider. This is important.
Contact a health care provider if you have:
• Swelling that gets worse or spreads to other areas.
• Problems with breathing.
• Lymph glands that:
◦ Are still swollen after 2 weeks.
◦ Have suddenly gotten bigger.
◦ Are red, painful, or hard.
• A fever or chills.
• Fatigue.
• A sore throat.
• Pain in your abdomen.
• Weight loss.
• Night sweats.
Get help right away if you have:
• Fluid leaking from an enlarged lymph gland.
• Severe pain.
• Chest pain.
• Shortness of breath.
Summary
• Lymphadenopathy means that your lymph glands are swollen or larger than normal (enlarged).
• Lymph glands (also called lymph nodes) are collections of tissue that filter bacteria, viruses, and waste from the bloodstream. They are part of your body's disease-fighting Butler (immune Butler).
• Lymphadenopathy can occur anywhere that you have lymph glands.
• If your enlarged and swollen lymph glands do not go back to normal after you have an infection or disease, your health care provider may do tests to monitor your condition and find the reason why the glands are still swollen and enlarged.
• Check your affected lymph glands every day for changes. Check other lymph gland areas as told by your health care provider.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
